&lt;h3&gt;Your Mission, Should You Choose to Accept:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Expensify prides itself on solving real-world problems with a team of top-notch product experts. We are reinventing the way people look at expense reports by automating not just the expense report, but the entire business trip. Joining our team means you are helping us fight the good fight against expense reports that suck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3&gt;About The Job&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;As a Success Coach, you will be focused on making sure that our customers are successful in using Expensify to solve the problems they face. You’ll do this by applying a deep understanding of our customers, their processes, our product and the systems with which we integrate. You’ll also gather feedback on how we can evolve Expensify to meet our customer’s needs in the future, and apply your product knowledge to map out these improvements for engineering. When product changes happen, you’ll lead the charge via documentation, blog posts, emails, calls and in-person visits with our customers.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Joining our team means you will be working in our fast-paced environment and you are fearless of our next big challenge. Even though we work hard at Expensify, we make sure our employees are happy. Our most-discussed perk is our offshore, where we spend a month abroad working as a team from a remote location. Last year we went to Cambodia and Thailand. Where do you want to go next?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3&gt;About You&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;You’re an entrepreneur who enjoys thinking through challenging problems, working across functional groups and articulating yourself in both technical and non-technical settings. You’re poised and confident when talking to customers and can always find the time to work with your colleagues to get any issue resolved.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;For the best possible fit, we are looking for someone who:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Has excellent communication skills. One moment you may be having a technical discussion with an engineer about the product implications of a new feature, the next moment need to communicate how we are going to sell this feature with a member of the sales team, before quickly moving on to working directly with a non-technical customer to fix a problem. The ideal candidate will be able to clearly articulate themselves in all scenarios.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Is passionate about building, maintaining and making our software better. It’s what we do as a company.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Can manage time and prioritize efficiently. Things move quickly in this environment and it’s crucial that you are able to react to new information and re-prioritize accordingly.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Is comfortable learning from peers in an informal fashion. After all, we&#39;re all learning things as we go. We also love anyone who&#39;s able to effectively train colleagues as we grow the team.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Is well-versed in saying “no”. We often have to say no to ensure that our product stays simple and user-friendly. Saying no and having a compelling argument as to why requires in-depth product knowledge and knowledge of the problem that the customer is trying to solve and is critical to success in this role.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3&gt;Next Steps&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Like what you see? Applying is easy, but it takes time. See, while we know you&#39;re awesome, it&#39;s actually really hard and time consuming to find you in the midst of literally hundreds of other applications we get from everyone else. So this is where we&#39;re going to ask our first favor: can you make it really easy and obvious how great you are, so we don&#39;t accidentally overlook you? There are probably many ways to do that, but the easiest way is to help us out by answering the following questions:&lt;/p&gt;
